<subsection xml:id="subsec-surface-area-of-a-cylinder">
    <title>Surface area of a cylinder</title>
    <p>
        The surface area of a cylinder is the total area of the curved surface and the two circular bases of the cylinder. 
       </p>

       <activity>
        <statement>
            <p>
                Surface Area Formula for Cylinders

            </p>

            <p>
                <ul>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            Open up a cylinder and make observations about its surface area using its net.
                        </p>
                    </li>
                </ul>
            </p>

                <figure>
                    <caption></caption>
                    <interactive xml:id="geogebra-cylinder1" geogebra="qfw3vbyy" width="100%" aspect="9:7" reset-icon="yes"/>
                </figure>
        </statement>
       </activity>

       <activity>
        <statement>
            <p>
                Work in groups
            </p>

            <p>
                Use the applet to review the formula for total surface area of a cylinder.
            </p>

            <p>
                
              Use the slider  Close = Net =open or click on the play  button to see an animation of the net of the cylinder!
            </p>

                <figure>
                    <caption></caption>
                    <interactive xml:id="geogebra-cylinder2" geogebra="uxwtsjbw" width="100%" aspect="9:7" reset-icon="yes"/>
                </figure>
        </statement>
       </activity>

       <example>
        <statement>
            <p>
                The figure below shows a cylinder whose radius and height are <m>14</m><m>cm</m>.and <m>15</m><m>cm</m> respectively.
            </p>

            <image>
            <latex-image>
                \begin{tikzpicture}
              % Define colors
    \definecolor{myblue}{rgb}{0.3, 0.6, 1.0}
    \definecolor{mygreen}{rgb}{0.0, 0.8, 0.0}
    \definecolor{mypurple}{rgb}{0.6, 0.2, 1.0}
    
    % Draw the cylinder
    \shade[bottom color=mygreen, top color=myblue, opacity=0.5] (0,0) ellipse (2 and 0.5);
    \draw[thick, black] (0,0) ellipse (2 and 0.5);
    \draw[thick, black] (-2,0) -- (-2,4);
    \draw[thick, black] (2,0) -- (2,4);
    \shade[bottom color=mygreen, top color=white, opacity=0.5] (0,4) ellipse (2 and 0.5);
    \draw[thick, mypurple] (0,4) ellipse (2 and 0.5);
    
    % Radius annotation
    \draw[dashed] (0,4) -- (1.5,4);
    \draw[thick] (1.5,4) -- (1.5,3.8) -- (0,3.8);
    \node[right] at (1.5,4) {\small $r$};

    % Height annotation
    \draw[dashed] (0,0) -- (0,4);
    \node[right] at (0,2) {\small $h$};
                \end{tikzpicture}
            </latex-image>
                <shortdescription></shortdescription>
                
            </image>

            <p>
                (a). Sketch the net of the cylinder.
            </p>

            <p>
                (b). Work out the surface area of the cylinder from its net.
            </p>
        </statement>

        <solution>
            <p>
                (a).The net of the cylinder is shown below
            </p>

            <p>
                <md>
                    <mrow>\text{(b). Length of the rectangle=} \amp 2 \times \pi \times radius </mrow>
                    <mrow>= \amp 2\times\frac{22}{7}\times14</mrow>
                    <mrow>= \amp 88 cm</mrow>
                </md>
            </p>
            <p>
                The width of the rectangle is equal to the height of the cylinder =<m>15</m><m>cm</m>
            </p>

            <p>
                <md>
                    <mrow>\text{Area of the rectangle}= \amp length \times width </mrow>
                    <mrow>= \amp88 cm \times 15 cm </mrow>
                    <mrow>= \amp1320 cm^2 </mrow>
                    <mrow>\text{Area of two circles}= \amp2\times \pi\times r^2 </mrow>
                    <mrow>= \amp 2\times \frac{22}{7}\times14 \times14</mrow>
                    <mrow>= \amp1232 cm^2 </mrow>
                    <mrow>\text{Surface area}= \amp1329 cm^2 +1232 cm^2 </mrow>
                    <mrow>= \amp2552 cm^2 </mrow>
                </md>
            </p>
        </solution>
       </example>
    
